## 1. Purpose

This Customer Requirement Specification (CRS) defines the product-level customer
requirements and the operating context for {{ project_name }}. It serves as the
formal customer-facing requirements document within the Design History File
(DHF) while also recording the stable product direction that shapes those
requirements.

{{ project_name }} is developed as an AI-native, design-controlled medical
software delivery system built from a single tooling-first repository:

- `medharness` is the orchestration CLI, CI gate logic, and scaffolding system
- `dhfkit` is the reusable DHF engine for items, traceability, lifecycle,
  and document generation — bundled in the same repository

The product goal is to constrain implementation by design and traceability so
that engineering work, AI-assisted workflows, and formal DHF records stay aligned
throughout the software lifecycle.

## 2. Intended Users and Environment

### 2.1 Intended Users

The primary users are software teams building medical device software under
design control, including:

- software engineers implementing regulated product behavior
- systems and software architects defining traceable designs
- quality and regulatory contributors reviewing DHF structure and evidence
- AI-assisted development agents operating under explicit project constraints

### 2.2 Intended Environment

The product is intended for repository-centric development environments that use:

- Git-based source control and pull-request review
- a product repository for source code, tests, and product CI
- a DHF repository for controlled requirements, design, risk, and traceability artifacts
- Python-based command-line tooling for scaffolding, validation, and evidence handling
- CI infrastructure that can execute tests, store JUnit XML, and publish build artifacts

The product is not positioned as a standalone compliance portal or document
management suite. It assumes that teams work in code, documents, Git history,
and CI systems.

## 3. Product Context

{{ project_name }} operates in a single tooling repository that generates
separate product and DHF repositories. Product code and test execution remain
in the product repository, while design-controlled DHF content remains in the
DHF repository. The orchestration and engine layers cooperate at runtime:

- the DHF repository defines the allowed structure, item schemas, and document templates
- the harness reads DHF structure to drive product-side coverage and evidence workflows
- AI guidance is derived from controlled documents, repo guidance files, and workflow prompts
- formal DHF documents are generated from controlled templates and item data in the DHF repository

This structure allows engineering workflows to move quickly without collapsing
design control into ad hoc narrative notes or disconnected spreadsheets.

## 4. Roadmap

### 4.1 Phase 1: Core Tooling

Establish the single-repo tooling baseline:

- DHF repo scaffolding from bundled templates via `medharness init`
- product CI scaffolding in `medharness`
- controlled DHF item model, document templates, and `dhfkit` operations
- requirement-to-test coverage and structural traceability workflows

### 4.2 Phase 2: Enhanced Workflows

Improve the quality of AI-assisted change execution by expanding:

- CR-driven planning and development flows
- document-grounded agent guidance
- design-aware review and verification support
- richer evidence capture from normal engineering workflows

### 4.3 Phase 3: Hardened Adoption

Focus on stability and adoption across real product programs through:

- more robust onboarding and migration paths
- broader verification workflow support
- improved operational documentation and audit readiness outputs
- continued refinement of the orchestration/engine layer boundaries

